{"id":"1609.06704","submitter":"Mark T. Mitchison","authors":"Paul Erker, Mark T. Mitchison, Ralph Silva, Mischa P. Woods, Nicolas\n  Brunner, Marcus Huber","title":"Autonomous quantum clocks: does thermodynamics limit our ability to\n  measure time?","comments":"Close to published version. 7+5 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. X 7, 031022 (2017)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevX.7.031022","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Time remains one of the least well understood concepts in physics, most\nnotably in quantum mechanics. A central goal is to find the fundamental limits\nof measuring time. One of the main obstacles is the fact that time is not an\nobservable and thus has to be measured indirectly. Here we explore these\nquestions by introducing a model of time measurements that is complete and\nautonomous. Specifically, our autonomous quantum clock consists of a system out\nof thermal equilibrium --- a prerequisite for any system to function as a clock\n--- powered by minimal resources, namely two thermal baths at different\ntemperatures. Through a detailed analysis of this specific clock model, we find\nthat the laws of thermodynamics dictate a trade-off between the amount of\ndissipated heat and the clock's performance in terms of its accuracy and\nresolution. Our results furthermore imply that a fundamental entropy production\nis associated with the operation of any autonomous quantum clock, assuming that\nquantum machines cannot achieve perfect efficiency at finite power. More\ngenerally, autonomous clocks provide a natural framework for the exploration of\nfundamental questions about time in quantum theory and beyond.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 21 Sep 2016 19:51:41 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 8 Dec 2016 20:59:38 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 4 Aug 2017 23:15:48 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-08-08"}
